A good designer listens and UNDERSTANDS how a family lives, how people may use their space, takes into account location, climate, durability, and cleanability. Why join another Facebook group when most are on instagram? Here is my breakdown of social:

1. Facebook is for photos of families and growth, grandkids and article shares. It’s groups are longer format education opportunities in specialty groups that align with your interests. Allows me to share more education and behind the scenes with the “why”.

You should join our Facebook group today (inside by Savvy)

A recent client asked a question in response to collecting 100% of our design fee upfront. He said, what if we don’t like the designs when they are done? I explained our 8 step process, how we have several touchpoints along the way, and how the design discovery process eliminates this. A failure to like the final design is truly reflective of a few things. 1. The design team did not do enough discovery (this has happened only once when the wife didn’t understand what the husband wanted and he was not at a single meeting) 2. You don’t know what you want and you struggle with decisions 3. You don’t share enough of what you like, what you don’t like and what your expectations are. Regardless, I have never (other than once with a past designer) not nailed a presentation with little to no edits, because listening is a skill not every design team has outside of Savvy. This is why I am there at every kick off meeting where we do a DEEP dive into what is important to you and your space so I truly understand the direction we are going. At the conclusion of our call, our new clients are much more in step with how we will knock this out of the park. :)

What are Savvy Standards? They are documents we continually update month over month that specify my design preferences in putting remodels together so the team works on designing something I don’t feel needs to be corrected, or altered. Kind of like a road map to preferences like “no schluter unless approved” or “no t moldings, I want the tile and the wood to butt up together with expandable grout joints”. These standards makes sure our quality and design detail is specific to us. Standards are also outlined for our subcontractors on “how we like it” which saves our clients time because we have less instruction to our team of subs. Standards can change, styles do, scale changes over time, but overall these guideposts help make our designs cohesive. @sandiegomarbleandtile

Lets talk Lighting . . . what is a lumen? a lumen is the unit of luminous flux, a measure of the total quantity of visible light emitted by a source per unit of time, in the International System of Units. In our terms, it means how much light a light can give off. A sitting room or bedroom will generally require around 10-20 lumens per square foot, while a bathroom or kitchen will need a stronger level of lighting, at around 70-80 lumens per square foot.

Let's talk about the art of styling, shall we? From books to baubles, here's how to turn those plain old planks into a showcase worthy of a standing ovation. 🙌🏼

1️⃣ Mix it up: Don't be afraid to play with a blend of vertical and horizontal arrangements. Tilt some books sideways, stack others upright, and sprinkle in beautifully curated objects for a touch of whimsy.
2️⃣ Play the texture game: Add visual interest by mixing textures like woven baskets, metallic accents, and sculptural ceramics. It's like a textural dance party that will make your shelves scream "style goals!"
3️⃣ Embrace the power of negative space: Don't overcrowd those shelves. Let your treasures breathe and create moments of pause. Gorgeous design needs room to shine, just like you on the dance floor.
4️⃣ Add a personal touch: Show off your personality by including quirky trinkets, meaningful mementos, or a collection of funky souvenirs. Let your shelves tell your unique story.
5️⃣ Oh, the magic of greenery: Sprinkle in some green goodness with potted plants or fresh-cut flowers. Not only do they bring life to your shelves, but they also purify the air and make you look like a responsible adult.

So, my friends, let's channel our inner shelf-styling gurus and create a masterpiece that would make Marie Kondo shed a happy tear.  #ShelfieGoals

We are already looking ahead to 2024 and all of the fun trends that are on the horizon. Here are some of our favorites we’ve gathered so far: 

1. Honoring slow living and the art of living in slow motion, and finding new ways of creating spaces focusing on functional cocoon layouts and being more responsible in our choices.
2. Statement sofas with curved and modular shapes.
3. More colors, dopamine decor, comeback of the Memphis movement. Bold and vivid interiors. 
4. The return of geometric patterns, not just exclusive to furniture, curves inspired by the 70’s and 80’s.
5. Artisanal revival- arts and craft furniture and statement pieces. Handmade pieces can add value to the interiors by sharing cultural values and emphasizing quality.
6. Versatile pieces that can be used indoors and outdoors.
7. Return of antique style- it honors the world’s legacy and also encourages sustainability by bringing in vintage pieces to reuse what has already been produced.

Choosing the correct colors for your interior design can make a significant difference in the overall ambiance and feel of your space. Here are some tips to help you make the right color choices:⁠
⁠
1. Consider the room's purpose: Think about the function of the room and the mood you want to create. Calming colors like blues and greens are great for bedrooms, while vibrant and energetic colors like yellows and oranges work well in living spaces.⁠
2. Determine your color scheme: Decide whether you want a monochromatic, complementary, or contrasting color scheme. Monochromatic uses different shades of one color, complementary pairs colors opposite each other on the color wheel, and contrasting combines colors from different sections of the color wheel.⁠
3. Take lighting into account: Natural and artificial lighting can affect how colors appear in a room. Consider the amount and type of lighting in the space when choosing colors. Test paint or fabric samples under different lighting conditions to see how they look.⁠
4. Consider the size of the room: Dark colors can make a room feel smaller, while light colors can make it feel more spacious. If you have a small space, opt for lighter colors to create an open and airy feel.⁠
5. Use color psychology: Colors can evoke different emotions and moods. For example, blues and greens promote relaxation and tranquility, while reds and oranges create energy and excitement. Consider the atmosphere you want to create and choose colors that align with that.

Hosting for the holidays? Here are some tips on how to best prepare your home for holiday guests: ⁠
⁠
Clean and Declutter: Tidy up your home, ensure the bathroom is clean and kitchen counters are cleared. This not only makes your home more welcoming but also makes post-party cleanup easier.⁠
⁠
Prepare the Guest Room: If you're expecting overnight guests, ensure your guest room is ready. Fresh linens, extra blankets, and toiletries can make your guests feel at home.⁠
⁠
Set the Mood: Use holiday decor to create a festive atmosphere. Lights, candles, and holiday centerpieces can transform your home into a holiday haven.⁠
⁠
Set Up a Beverage Station: Set up a self-serve bar or beverage station where guests can help themselves. This reduces your hosting duties and allows guests to mix their preferred drinks.⁠
⁠
Relax and Enjoy: Remember, the holiday season is about enjoying time with loved ones. Don't stress over small details and make sure to take time to enjoy the festivities yourself.⁠
⁠
